  "why": "The paper's semSensFuzz / semImFuzz design explicitly assumes and enforces semantically valid, realistic inputs. It scopes allowed mutations by the original test interpretations, requires preconditions (based on the original interp) for mutation applicability, and parameterizes image edits using real sensor data (resources) to preserve pose, perspective, and lighting. The implementation further applies concrete conformity checks (vanishing-point quadrant matching, brightness/HSV median threshold, placement on road, bounding-size thresholds, occlusion filtering) so mutated inputs remain realistic. Additionally, the approach mutates the interpretation symmetrically (so semantics are preserved and oracle expectations remain valid). The tool also performs single semantic mutations referenced to original seeds/resources (not iteratively chaining mutations on mutants), avoiding cumulative drift. These design and implementation choices satisfy the metric’s requirements for enforcing both semantic consistency and naturalness across fuzzing iterations (i.e., preserving semantics relative to original seeds and ensuring realism).",
